line=21 fonts=F2-10.9 bbox=82.92,299.16,525.69,310.07                    :  In these examples, the subject NP is coindexed with the missing object of the embedded predicate.
line=22 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,285.6,525.68,296.51          :This relationship between the subject NP and missing object has been considered to be a long-distance
line=23 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,272.04,525.66,282.95         :dependency  because in principle there is no bound on the depth of embedding of the missing object. This
line=24 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.28 bbox=72.0,258.54,525.59,269.45         :dependency, however, is not the same as the filler-gap dependency seen in wh-phrase constructions; the
line=25 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,244.98,391.63,255.89         :subject NP and a missing object do not need to have the same case in (1).
line=26 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.27 bbox=82.92,231.42,525.64,242.33:  In Korean, a group of adjectives semantically similar to the English tough predicates exhibits similar
line=27 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.00 bbox=72.0,217.86,525.65,228.77 :behavior; this group includes swipta ‘easy’, elyepta ‘hard’, pulkanunghata ‘impossible’, etc. Consider
line=28 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.08 bbox=72.0,204.3,176.79,215.21          :the following examples.

