line=82 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 bbox=82.92,703.98,525.62,714.89            :  Second, Korean tough predicates subcategorize for so-called nominalized gerund phrases (NGPs) with
line=83 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,690.48,525.7,701.39  :ki. While ki NGPs  occur as subject, object, or oblique with a case marker, their internal argument
line=84 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.16 bbox=72.0,676.92,525.53,687.83         :realization is the same as that of a VP or an S. We claim that NGPs have the status of VPs or Ss and that
line=85 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.20 bbox=72.0,663.36,525.53,674.27 :ki is a morphological complementizer that marks the whole phrase as one constituent. However, we use
line=86 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.38 bbox=72.0,649.8,525.69,660.71          :thetermNGPsforki    phrases since NPGs have been widely used in Korean grammar. We  will discuss
line=87 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.07 bbox=72.0,636.24,181.74,647.15         :this in detail in section 4.
line=88 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.00 bbox=82.92,622.68,525.65,633.59:  Third, ki-ey TCs and ki-ka TCs are similar in that they can be combined with the same kind of matrix
