line=125 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 bbox=82.92,622.68,525.69,633.59           :  Semantically, a ki-ey phrase in a TC is interpreted as a goal event that is closely related to the properties
line=126 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,609.18,525.68,620.09:of the subject NP. We know  that a ki-ey NP refers to an event that corresponds to a goal or standard
line=127 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.38 bbox=72.0,595.62,525.58,606.53        :because it can be paraphrased into ‘in order to achieve the goal of’ or ‘in order to satisfy the standard of
line=128 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,582.06,525.64,592.97:’. In addition, the subject NP refers to an entity that achieves that goal or standard. Unlike ki-ka phrases,
line=129 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.32 bbox=72.0,568.5,525.59,579.41 :ki-ey phrases also appear with predicates subcategorizing for a goal element such as pwucekhaphata ‘be
line=130 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.27 bbox=72.0,554.94,482.31,565.85:inappropriate’, kelmacta ‘be proper’, mocaluta ‘be lacking’, chungpwunhata ‘be enough’, etc.

