line=313 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 bbox=82.92,286.92,525.66,297.83            :  Tough  predicates like swipta ‘easy’, himtulta ‘tough’, and elyepta ‘hard’ subcategorize for a ki-ey
line=314 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.13 bbox=72.0,273.36,525.62,284.27         :phrase in their COMPS  list. We use ARG(ument)-ST(ructure)  that has the features SUBJ, SPR, and
line=315 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,259.86,525.56,270.77 :COMPS,   just as valence structures do, following Pollard (1994). The ki-ey phrase must contain an NP
line=316 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.11 bbox=72.0,246.3,525.6,257.21   :gap coindexed with the subject of swipta ‘easy’. The SLASH value that originates in a ki-ey phrase is
line=317 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,232.74,525.68,243.65 :bound by TO-BIND   SLASH   feature of swipta. This is represented by the SLASH feature in the lexical
line=318 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,219.18,186.99,230.09 :entry of a tough predicate.
line=319 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=82.92,205.62,525.59,216.53:  With  respect to ki phrases, the status of nominalized phrases has been controversial in the Korean
line=320 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=72.0,192.12,423.85,203.03         :grammar. We  can summarize the general properties of Korean NGPS as follows:

doc_id=46 page=8 block_id=8-7 bbox=72.0,50.52,525.73,179.51 label=bb 321 330
line=321 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9,F5-5.5 bbox=83.4,168.6,525.59,179.51         :   ffl There are two nominalizers, ki and um, which attach to a stem of a predicate. The realization of
line=322 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=93.84,155.04,525.73,165.95  :     the ki and um  phrases is restricted according to the matrix predicates. Semantically, nominalizer
line=323 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.07 bbox=93.84,141.48,525.66,152.39  :     ki combines  with event or active predicates, while um combines with descriptive or inactive predi-
line=324 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=93.84,127.92,525.57,138.83  :     cates. The main  predicate subcategorizing for an NGP  determines whether  it selects a ki phrase or
line=325 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=93.84,114.36,525.65,125.27  :     a um phrase. It is commonly  accepted that ki refers to nonfactual events while um refers to factual
line=326 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.15 bbox=93.83,100.86,525.54,111.77  :     events. In TCs, a stem of a predicate combining with ki is restricted to the base form, while in other
line=327 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.10 bbox=93.83,87.3,368.91,98.21     :     constructions, a tense or agreement morpheme  can precedes  ki.
line=328 fonts=F1-9.0,F2-6.0,F2-9.0 iscore=0.05 bbox=84.66,70.44,525.56,80.2:   ^{6}As argued by Cho (1995), a untensed phrase with the conjunctive -ko is ambiguous between a temporal adjunct phrase
line=329 fonts=F2-9.0 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,60.48,525.71,69.45              :and a coordinate structure. Thus, Aross-The-Board (ATB) violation is allowed for adjunct structures but not for coordinate
line=330 fonts=F2-9.0 iscore=0.06 bbox=72.0,50.52,146.62,59.49              :structures in Korean.

doc_id=46 page=9 block_id=9-1 bbox=83.4,690.48,525.6,714.89 label=tt 331 332
line=331 fonts=F2-10.9,F5-5.5 bbox=83.4,703.98,525.6,714.89       :  ffl It has been argued that NGPs have dual status; there is no change of internal arguments as in a VP
line=332 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.15 bbox=93.84,690.48,333.84,701.39:     or an S, but they combines with case markers like NPs.

doc_id=46 page=9 block_id=9-2 bbox=83.4,587.16,525.71,679.37 label=tb 333 339
line=333 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9,F5-5.5 bbox=83.4,668.46,525.58,679.37             :  ffl There are word-level deverbal affixes ki and um distinguished from phrase-level nominalizers ki
line=334 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.19 bbox=93.84,654.9,525.59,665.81        :     and um in Korean. The word-level affixes ki and um attach to a stem of a verb or an adjective and
line=335 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.24 bbox=93.84,641.34,525.65,652.25       :     change the lexical category into a noun as in talli-ki ‘running’, ilk-ki ‘reading’, po-ki ‘example’.
line=336 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.13 bbox=93.84,627.78,525.52,638.69               :     There are different morphosyntactic and semantic properties between these two kinds, which has
line=337 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9,F2-8.0 iscore=0.20 bbox=93.84,614.22,525.71,626.15:     been discussed in Yoon (1996) and Kaiser (1997).^{7} ki and um have been respectively distinguished
line=338 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.13 bbox=93.84,600.66,525.59,611.57               :     into two different morphemes introducing lexical nominalization and phrasal nominalization. Only
line=339 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.09 bbox=93.84,587.16,256.08,598.07               :     phrasal nominalization involves TCs.

doc_id=46 page=9 block_id=9-3 bbox=72.0,388.86,525.74,575.93 label=bt 340 353
line=340 fonts=F2-10.9 bbox=82.92,565.02,525.62,575.93                    :  There are three kinds of approaches to phrasal nominalization in Korean. The first argues that the
line=341 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.05 bbox=72.0,551.46,525.59,562.37 :phrasal nominalizer ki is applied at the level of syntax while the second argues that it is introduced at
line=342 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,537.9,525.74,548.81          :the morphological level. For example, Yoon (1996) and  Kaiser (1997) propose a syntactic approach
line=343 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.12 bbox=72.0,524.34,525.56,535.25         :to phrasal nominalization by putting the nominalizer in a separate syntactic node or a phrasal affix,
line=344 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.31 bbox=72.0,510.78,525.62,521.69         :respectively. The affix combines with a VP and projects a nominal structure. The second approach is
line=345 fonts=F2-10.9,F5-5.5 iscore=0.38 bbox=72.0,497.28,525.58,508.19  :the lexical approach of Lapointe and Nielsen (1994). They propose a dual lexical category, hNjVi for
line=346 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.16 bbox=72.0,483.72,525.59,494.63 :gerunds. They combine  the affix ki with a verbal stem instead of putting it in a separate syntactic node.
line=347 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,470.16,525.55,481.07         :The third approach is a mixed category analysis of Chang et al. (2001) similar to Malouf (2000). They
line=348 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.17 bbox=72.0,456.6,525.68,467.51  :argue that gerund has a subtype of nominal and verb on the basis the multiple inheritance type hierarchy.
line=349 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.29 bbox=82.92,443.04,525.57,453.95:  Without assuming  mixed category of gerunds, we claim that ki phrases maintain the status of VPs or
line=350 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.28 bbox=72.0,429.48,525.61,440.39 :Ss and ki nominalizer marks them as functioning similar to NPs. Thrre is no change in the morphosyn-
line=351 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.28 bbox=72.0,415.98,525.54,426.89         :tactic status of VPs or Ss with nominalizing complementizers. Case marking has been used as the main
line=352 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.28 bbox=72.0,402.42,525.54,413.33 :supporting evidence for the argument that ki or um marked phrases are NPs. However, some VPs or Ss
line=353 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.28 bbox=72.0,388.86,466.06,399.77         :which ends with certain predicate suffixes can be combined with a case marker as follows.

