doc_id=46 page=11 block_id=11-5 bbox=72.0,177.54,525.76,283.31 label=btbtb 428 435
line=428 fonts=F2-10.9 bbox=72.0,272.4,525.64,283.31                     :In this paper, we have examined the characteristic properties of Korean TCs and given a structural anal-
line=429 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.35 bbox=72.0,258.84,525.59,269.75        :ysis of them. Various kinds of argument dependencies in Korean TCs are considered to be unbounded
line=430 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.35 bbox=72.0,245.28,525.43,256.19        :dependencies, and they can be represented by the SLASH feature and by binding within the lexical en-
line=431 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.24 bbox=72.0,231.78,525.58,242.69:tries of tough predicates. TC gaps in Korean are analyzed as traces rather than null pronominals that
line=432 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.18 bbox=72.0,218.22,525.76,229.13        :can be dropped based on contexts. Furthermore, we claim that a resumptive pronoun is another form
line=433 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,204.66,525.64,215.57:of a trace in Korean. Korean TCs are divided into ki-ey TCs and ki-ka TCs and we provided supporting
line=434 fonts=F2-10.9 iscore=0.21 bbox=72.0,191.1,525.71,202.01         :evidence to distinguish these two constructions. The unbounded dependency of elements can be lexically
line=435 fonts=F1-10.9,F2-10.9 iscore=0.29 bbox=72.0,177.54,501.2,188.45 :encoded in the lexical entries of tough predicates that have two different subcategorization frames.

